## Architecture Overview

### Stateless-First Design

Beach Concierge is architected as a **100% stateless static SPA** — there is no server-side session state, no database writes, and no authentication in the current phase.

```
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                        User Browser                          │
│                                                              │
│  index.html ──► script.js (single controller, ~4,500 loc)   │
│                     │                                        │
│              ┌──────┴───────┐                                │
│              │  In-Memory   │  localStorage                  │
│              │  State (cart)│  (history, social, noise map)  │
│              └──────┬───────┘                                │
└─────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────┘
                       │  fetch() — all connections whitelisted in CSP
          ┌────────────┼────────────────────────────┐
          ▼            ▼                            ▼
   Open-Meteo     Nominatim                    ipapi.co
  (weather/UV)   (reverse geocode)            (IP fallback)
```

**Why this matters for scale:**  
Every request is served from a CDN edge node. There is no application-server bottleneck, no database connection pool to exhaust, and no session affinity requirement. Cold-start time is zero. This architecture **trivially handles 1M+ daily users** because the server never executes any user-specific code — it only serves static bytes.

### Module Separation

| Layer | File | Responsibility |
|-------|------|----------------|
| **Presentation** | `index.html` | Document shell + security headers |
| **Styles** | `style.css` | All layout and theming (~2,130 lines) |
| **Controller** | `script.js` | App logic, DOM management (~4,550 lines) |
| **Core (testable)** | `src/core.js` | Pure business logic — no DOM, fully unit-tested |
| **Build config** | `vite.config.ts` | Bundler + dev-server HTTP security headers |

The `src/core.js` module exists as the **canonical, testable implementation** of every pure function. The browser bundle duplicates them inline for legacy compatibility — `core.js` is the authoritative test target.

